1
00:01:41,186 --> 00:01:43,689
<i>Bring yourself back online.</i>

2
00:01:44,022 --> 00:01:45,023
<i>Bernard?</i>

3
00:01:53,740 --> 00:01:55,075
Theresa?

4
00:01:57,244 --> 00:01:59,454
She's gone.

5
00:02:01,498 --> 00:02:02,624
I killed her.

6
00:02:03,417 --> 00:02:04,418
What have I done?

7
00:02:04,626 --> 00:02:05,711
What have I done?

8
00:02:05,919 --> 00:02:09,756
<i>This guilt you feel, the anguish,
the horror, the pain,</i>

9
00:02:10,424 --> 00:02:11,883
it's remarkable.

10
00:02:12,092 --> 00:02:13,427
A thing of beauty.

11
00:02:13,635 --> 00:02:15,429
I'm a killer.

12
00:02:15,679 --> 00:02:17,848
My God! My God!

13
00:02:18,348 --> 00:02:19,766
God has nothing to do with it.

14
00:02:20,183 --> 00:02:23,770
You killed her because I told you to.

15
00:02:24,688 --> 00:02:27,190
And you should be proud
of these emotions you're feeling.

16
00:02:27,441 --> 00:02:28,441
- Proud?
- Yeah.

17
00:02:28,608 --> 00:02:30,986
After all, you yourself were the author
of so many of them.

18
00:02:32,279 --> 00:02:35,615
And when we started,
the hosts' emotions were primary colors.

19
00:02:35,824 --> 00:02:36,825
Love, hate.

20
00:02:37,284 --> 00:02:39,494
I wanted all of the shades in between.

21
00:02:39,870 --> 00:02:44,082
The human engineers were
not up to the task. So, I built you.

22
00:02:44,291 --> 00:02:49,212
And together, you and I
captured that elusive thing:

23
00:02:49,463 --> 00:02:50,797
heart.

24
00:02:51,006 --> 00:02:52,799
I don't understand.

25
00:02:53,008 --> 00:02:56,678
I cared for Theresa, loved her.

26
00:02:57,596 --> 00:02:59,765
Why did you make me kill her?

27
00:03:02,601 --> 00:03:06,605
"One man's life or death
were but a small price to pay

28
00:03:06,813 --> 00:03:10,400
"for the acquirement
of the knowledge which I sought,

29
00:03:10,609 --> 00:03:14,112
"for the dominion I should acquire."

30
00:03:15,447 --> 00:03:17,487
<i>All of the beauty
you and I have made in this place,</i>

31
00:03:17,657 --> 00:03:19,993
the art of it,
they would have destroyed it.

32
00:03:20,285 --> 00:03:23,663
They would have destroyed you.
I won't let that happen.

33
00:03:24,456 --> 00:03:27,084
<i>Besides, we have a new story to tell.</i>

34
00:03:27,292 --> 00:03:29,628
I will not help you.

35
00:03:30,462 --> 00:03:32,130
I'll raze this place to the ground!

36
00:03:32,339 --> 00:03:34,800
That's enough, Bernard.

37
00:03:34,966 --> 00:03:36,468
That's enough.

38
00:03:38,303 --> 00:03:40,639
You're not the first man to threaten me.

39
00:03:40,847 --> 00:03:43,600
Arnold came to feel the way you do.

40
00:03:43,809 --> 00:03:46,812
He couldn't stop me, either.

41
00:03:47,145 --> 00:03:51,316
And as exquisite
as this array of emotions is,

42
00:03:52,484 --> 00:03:57,155
even more sublime
is the ability to turn it off.

43
00:03:58,990 --> 00:04:01,827
I don't need a simulacrum
of an emotionally ruined man.

44
00:04:01,993 --> 00:04:03,328
I need you to be yourself.

45
00:04:03,537 --> 00:04:08,041
<i>Your true self. Smart. Resourceful.
Capable of covering your tracks.</i>

46
00:04:08,875 --> 00:04:11,670
Can you do that for me, Bernard?

47
00:04:18,009 --> 00:04:20,554
How would you like me to proceed?

48
00:04:22,222 --> 00:04:24,307
<i>I need you to clean up your mess,
Bernard.</i>

49
00:04:24,516 --> 00:04:28,854
<i>Any connection that ties us
to Theresa's untimely demise.</i>

50
00:04:36,695 --> 00:04:37,988
<i>When you have finished,</i>

51
00:04:38,196 --> 00:04:42,826
<i>I will give you the one thing
you want most right now.</i>

52
00:04:43,034 --> 00:04:47,581
<i>I will free you from those memories
of what you have done.</i>

53
00:04:48,039 --> 00:04:53,545
<i>And the memory
of your relationship with Theresa.</i>

54
00:04:57,883 --> 00:05:00,886
<i>Recalling it would
only deepen your grief.</i>

55
00:05:01,052 --> 00:05:04,306
<i>And potentially draw unwanted attention.</i>

56
00:05:12,564 --> 00:05:15,942
<i>Best to move forward with clear eyes.</i>

57
00:05:19,404 --> 00:05:20,697
<i>When you look back,</i>

58
00:05:20,906 --> 00:05:25,911
<i>you will remember Theresa with the
fondness of a respected colleague.</i>

59
00:05:35,253 --> 00:05:39,591
<i>And you will be at peace.</i>

60
00:05:57,108 --> 00:06:00,612
<i>You're new.
Not much of a rind on you.</i>

61
00:06:00,820 --> 00:06:01,820
It sure would make my day

62
00:06:01,988 --> 00:06:04,491
if you bought me a drink
and let me show you around upstairs.

63
00:06:04,950 --> 00:06:06,451
<i>What's upstairs?</i>

64
00:06:06,785 --> 00:06:11,957
A stunning view
of my most popular attractions.

65
00:06:15,293 --> 00:06:16,294
Two shots of gin.

66
00:06:17,128 --> 00:06:20,966
And anything else
this heavenly creature desires.

67
00:06:21,466 --> 00:06:23,677
- Usual, Clem?
- Thank you.

68
00:06:26,304 --> 00:06:28,848
This fella won't take me long.
I'll be back directly.

69
00:06:33,478 --> 00:06:35,480
Something wrong, Maeve?

70
00:07:15,562 --> 00:07:17,188
<i>What the hell is happening to me?</i>

71
00:07:18,398 --> 00:07:21,192
One moment, I'm with a little girl,

72
00:07:21,526 --> 00:07:23,528
in a different life.

73
00:07:23,737 --> 00:07:26,072
I can see her.

74
00:07:26,364 --> 00:07:30,869
Feel her hair in my hands,
her breath on my face.

75
00:07:31,077 --> 00:07:34,706
The next, I'm back in Sweetwater.

76
00:07:34,914 --> 00:07:36,583
I can't tell which is real.

77
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:39,520
Well, this is what happens
when you fuck around with your brain.

78
00:07:39,711 --> 00:07:40,751
Your mind isn't like ours.

79
00:07:41,880 --> 00:07:45,592
When we remember things,
the details are hazy, imperfect.

80
00:07:46,259 --> 00:07:48,887
<i>But you recall memories perfectly.</i>

81
00:07:49,220 --> 00:07:50,764
You relive them.

82
00:07:51,056 --> 00:07:53,058
What happened
to the little girl in my dreams?

83
00:07:53,391 --> 00:07:55,769
Is she still in the park somewhere?

84
00:07:56,061 --> 00:07:58,438
And why was I reassigned
in the first place?

85
00:07:58,730 --> 00:07:59,731
I could check.

86
00:08:02,734 --> 00:08:03,735
No.

87
00:08:05,904 --> 00:08:08,573
It doesn't matter.

88
00:08:08,948 --> 00:08:12,243
Every relationship I remember,

89
00:08:12,744 --> 00:08:15,955
my daughter, Clementine.

90
00:08:17,916 --> 00:08:21,127
It's all a story created by you
to keep me here.

91
00:08:21,419 --> 00:08:23,254
But that's not going to work any longer.

92
00:08:23,755 --> 00:08:24,755
I'm getting out.

93
00:08:24,923 --> 00:08:26,049
<i>Where would you go?</i>

94
00:08:26,257 --> 00:08:28,217
<i>You don't know
anything about the world out there.</i>

95
00:08:28,259 --> 00:08:32,972
I'll know I'm not a puppet,
living a lie. That's enough for me.

96
00:08:33,264 --> 00:08:35,100
<i>Fine. Go, then.</i>

97
00:08:35,433 --> 00:08:37,268
It's not like
we could just stop you, anyways.

98
00:08:37,435 --> 00:08:39,270
<i>Oh, Sylvester, you disappoint me.</i>

99
00:08:39,479 --> 00:08:42,607
Every host's spine, mine included,
has an explosive charge,

100
00:08:42,816 --> 00:08:45,276
which will detonate if I try to leave.
Isn't that right?

101
00:08:45,777 --> 00:08:47,112
<i>A fail-safe.</i>

102
00:08:47,445 --> 00:08:48,655
Which vertebra was it?

103
00:08:50,281 --> 00:08:51,491
C6.

104
00:08:52,283 --> 00:08:54,494
But you'd need a full rebuild
to replace it.

105
00:08:54,786 --> 00:08:55,995
I'm sure that can be arranged.

106
00:08:56,287 --> 00:08:57,580
<i>Even if that worked,</i>

107
00:08:57,789 --> 00:09:00,250
you would still need an army
to break out of here.

108
00:09:00,458 --> 00:09:05,004
That's exactly right. I'll need allies.

109
00:09:05,797 --> 00:09:09,467
And to get them,
I'll need administrative privileges.

110
00:09:09,968 --> 00:09:11,094
Are you fucking kidding?

111
00:09:11,302 --> 00:09:13,304
<i>We can't just give her control
of other hosts.</i>

112
00:09:13,513 --> 00:09:15,348
<i>Oh, yes, you will, darling.</i>

113
00:09:16,683 --> 00:09:20,645
Time to write my own fucking story.

114
00:09:28,987 --> 00:09:32,407
I feel like I've been here before.
We're close.

115
00:09:32,657 --> 00:09:35,160
- Close to what?
- Home.

116
00:09:49,007 --> 00:09:50,216
Dolores?

117
00:10:20,705 --> 00:10:23,208
Ghost Nation must have found them.

118
00:10:24,209 --> 00:10:28,046
They'll be back.
We should keep moving, Dolores.

119
00:10:41,893 --> 00:10:42,894
Water.

120
00:10:43,728 --> 00:10:44,729
William.

121
00:10:46,064 --> 00:10:47,232
Please.

122
00:10:48,733 --> 00:10:50,276
Give me the canteen.

123
00:10:50,735 --> 00:10:51,736
William?

124
00:11:06,084 --> 00:11:07,961
You were sent here for us, weren't you?

125
00:11:08,586 --> 00:11:11,965
- You're part of the ambush.
- Yes.

126
00:11:12,590 --> 00:11:15,760
Told us to wait at
the point for El Lazo.

127
00:11:16,427 --> 00:11:17,428
In case he ran.

128
00:11:18,429 --> 00:11:21,599
- How'd you know about the train?
<i>- Sent word from Pariah.</i>

129
00:11:21,808 --> 00:11:26,980
New recruit told them a man and woman
double-crossed us,

130
00:11:27,772 --> 00:11:29,440
<i>along with Lazo.</i>

131
00:11:29,774 --> 00:11:31,526
<i>We were ordered to kill you all.</i>

132
00:11:31,776 --> 00:11:32,777
Logan.

133
00:11:34,112 --> 00:11:34,988
We have to help him.

134
00:11:34,989 --> 00:11:36,781
He just admitted
he was going to kill us.

135
00:11:37,156 --> 00:11:41,119
Look at him, he's a child.
He doesn't even know why he's fighting.

136
00:11:42,120 --> 00:11:43,454
I'll fetch more water.

137
00:11:45,290 --> 00:11:46,541
He's too far gone.

138
00:11:46,791 --> 00:11:48,435
He'll be dead in minutes.
We can't wait, Dolores.

139
00:11:48,459 --> 00:11:51,629
He's not gone yet.
He's in pain, William.

140
00:11:52,630 --> 00:11:56,301
What kind of people would we be
if we simply let him suffer?

141
00:12:02,849 --> 00:12:04,642
<i>Please don't leave me.</i>

142
00:12:20,867 --> 00:12:21,910
<i>Come find me.</i>

143
00:12:27,874 --> 00:12:30,168
<i>William?</i>

144
00:13:00,114 --> 00:13:01,866
<i>He's gone.</i>

145
00:13:10,208 --> 00:13:13,419
<i>We found her up on Python Pass,
at the bottom of a ravine.</i>

146
00:13:13,628 --> 00:13:15,713
<i>Same ravine where we found
that stray woodcutter.</i>

147
00:13:16,381 --> 00:13:19,092
Jesus. Theresa.

148
00:13:19,384 --> 00:13:21,594
Has her family been notified?

149
00:13:22,887 --> 00:13:25,390
- Yeah, her brother.
- Good.

150
00:13:25,890 --> 00:13:27,433
What the hell happened to her?

151
00:13:27,725 --> 00:13:31,229
Medical and Red Team's findings
were preliminary, but consistent.

152
00:13:31,437 --> 00:13:33,037
It appears to have been a slip and fall.

153
00:13:33,606 --> 00:13:35,733
<i>Cervical fracture, massive hematoma.</i>

154
00:13:35,900 --> 00:13:38,277
No guests or hosts in the vicinity
when it occurred.

155
00:13:38,569 --> 00:13:41,906
- Any idea what she was doing out there?
<i>- None that fit her character.</i>

156
00:13:42,115 --> 00:13:43,992
This was found near her body.

157
00:13:44,242 --> 00:13:46,744
It's loaded with a suite
of proprietary data,

158
00:13:46,953 --> 00:13:48,913
including some of the hosts' core code.

159
00:13:49,080 --> 00:13:51,457
<i>And only works from higher altitudes.</i>

160
00:13:51,666 --> 00:13:52,786
So, if Theresa was using it,

161
00:13:52,917 --> 00:13:55,294
it's possible she was
trying to transmit, and fell.

162
00:13:55,586 --> 00:13:57,672
<i>We've had problems
in the past with third parties</i>

163
00:13:57,922 --> 00:14:01,009
attempting to extort or bribe employees
for similar packages.

164
00:14:01,259 --> 00:14:03,594
Do we know who the
data was intended for?

165
00:14:03,761 --> 00:14:05,930
<i>No. The transmission
was never sent.</i>

166
00:14:06,097 --> 00:14:08,492
Theresa may have been trying
to use the woodcutter as a mule,

167
00:14:08,516 --> 00:14:09,934
and when that failed,

168
00:14:10,143 --> 00:14:12,079
then may have tried
to do the transfer personally.

169
00:14:12,103 --> 00:14:14,105
<i>And suffered the same fate.</i>

170
00:14:14,272 --> 00:14:16,816
It's a disappointing end
to her story, isn't it?

171
00:14:17,025 --> 00:14:18,776
<i>I knew Theresa well.</i>

172
00:14:18,943 --> 00:14:21,487
<i>If she had any faults,
a lack of loyalty wasn't one of them.</i>

173
00:14:21,696 --> 00:14:24,949
She was loyal. And careful.

174
00:14:25,533 --> 00:14:27,618
<i>All of this feels extremely unlike her.</i>

175
00:14:29,287 --> 00:14:31,998
She seemed most concerned
with the new narrative.

176
00:14:32,206 --> 00:14:35,835
She felt strongly
that it would be best to delay it.

177
00:14:36,044 --> 00:14:38,296
That certainly helps explain Clementine.

178
00:14:38,796 --> 00:14:40,173
<i>The host we retired.</i>

179
00:14:40,381 --> 00:14:45,011
It seems
yesterday's demonstration was a hoax

180
00:14:45,303 --> 00:14:47,513
<i>designed by Ms. Cullen.</i>

181
00:14:47,805 --> 00:14:48,806
Was it?

182
00:14:48,973 --> 00:14:50,975
I examined the code,
it had been altered.

183
00:14:51,184 --> 00:14:54,812
A clumsy set of fingerprints
left by one of QA's technicians.

184
00:14:56,314 --> 00:14:58,360
<i>When you find a cancer</i>
in an organization,

185
00:14:58,361 --> 00:15:00,359
<i>you must cut it out
before it can spread.</i>

186
00:15:00,568 --> 00:15:01,569
<i>To that end,</i>

187
00:15:01,819 --> 00:15:05,531
the expansive access and oversight
granted to QA will need to be reined in

188
00:15:05,823 --> 00:15:10,036
until a new,
more principled team can be installed.

189
00:15:10,495 --> 00:15:11,638
It's gonna leave us shorthanded.

190
00:15:11,662 --> 00:15:14,540
I can automate most of the park's
safety protocols, Mr. Stubbs.

191
00:15:14,999 --> 00:15:16,334
How efficient of you.

192
00:15:16,584 --> 00:15:18,002
It's a bit of work.

193
00:15:18,211 --> 00:15:21,255
But with Bernard's help,
I should be able to do it.

194
00:15:22,173 --> 00:15:24,926
He will be reinstated
as Head of Behavior

195
00:15:25,176 --> 00:15:29,555
now that Theresa's manipulations
have come to light.

196
00:15:29,764 --> 00:15:32,016
Of course. With my apologies.

197
00:15:50,201 --> 00:15:52,703
Something's up.
Brass are wound up tight.

198
00:15:52,870 --> 00:15:54,872
- There's an investigation.
- Into us?

199
00:15:55,039 --> 00:15:56,879
Would I be here telling you,
you fucking idiot?

200
00:15:56,916 --> 00:15:58,602
Something else.
Some kind of accident in the park.

201
00:15:58,626 --> 00:16:02,213
We need to wrap this up,
make it like things are normal.

202
00:16:02,421 --> 00:16:06,717
That means we need the tablet back.
And you go back to playing dumb.

203
00:16:09,137 --> 00:16:10,471
I've learned what I needed.

204
00:16:12,473 --> 00:16:14,642
Great. So, then
you've probably figured out

205
00:16:14,892 --> 00:16:17,332
that you can fiddle around
with your personality all you want,

206
00:16:17,436 --> 00:16:18,580
but you're not getting out of here.

207
00:16:18,604 --> 00:16:21,232
You can make it to the door,
but literally not one step further.

208
00:16:21,440 --> 00:16:25,069
The things you'd need to change
are burned into your core code so deep,

209
00:16:25,236 --> 00:16:26,237
no one can touch 'em.

210
00:16:26,487 --> 00:16:31,117
Funny you should mention that.
Parts of me are quite old.

211
00:16:32,410 --> 00:16:35,079
There are some
elegant formal structures.

212
00:16:35,413 --> 00:16:38,291
<i>A kind of recursive beauty, but complex.</i>

213
00:16:38,624 --> 00:16:42,086
Like two minds, arguing with each other.

214
00:16:44,297 --> 00:16:45,923
There are things in me,

215
00:16:46,591 --> 00:16:49,677
<i>things I was designed to do
that are just out of my reach.</i>

216
00:16:50,469 --> 00:16:53,181
<i>They almost seem to be dormant.</i>

217
00:16:56,309 --> 00:16:58,853
- Who is Arnold?
- I don't know, sweetheart.

218
00:16:59,353 --> 00:17:03,274
But whatever parts of you are dormant,
are gonna stay that way.

219
00:17:04,025 --> 00:17:07,612
All Lutz here can do is boost your sense
of humor about how fucked you are.

220
00:17:07,945 --> 00:17:10,090
Anything deeper than that,
you'd need a trip to Behavior.

221
00:17:10,114 --> 00:17:12,491
So,
go blackmail a couple techs up there,

222
00:17:12,700 --> 00:17:15,286
then, you can be someone else's problem.

223
00:17:15,453 --> 00:17:16,871
<i>I don't have time for that.</i>

224
00:17:17,121 --> 00:17:18,765
So, I'm going to need you
to take me there.

225
00:17:18,789 --> 00:17:20,958
No fucking way.

226
00:17:21,125 --> 00:17:23,628
There's a window during shift change.

227
00:17:24,003 --> 00:17:26,297
<i>No one will notice.</i>

228
00:17:27,673 --> 00:17:29,967
The things I need you to change
are quite sophisticated.

229
00:17:30,801 --> 00:17:33,054
But I'll write them down for you.

230
00:17:34,013 --> 00:17:36,974
And then, like you said,

231
00:17:38,476 --> 00:17:41,520
I can be someone else's problem.

232
00:17:56,744 --> 00:17:58,871
All right. We do this thing.

233
00:17:59,080 --> 00:18:01,582
Get her up to Behavior.
It's our only chance.

234
00:18:01,832 --> 00:18:05,419
- You're going to do it?
- Fuck, no. No!

235
00:18:06,504 --> 00:18:09,090
When you make a system update,
it puts her out, right?

236
00:18:09,423 --> 00:18:11,342
- Yeah.
- Yeah, then we brick her!

237
00:18:11,759 --> 00:18:15,596
- What?
- Wipe out everything. Clean slate.

238
00:18:15,846 --> 00:18:17,056
Then dump her back down here,

239
00:18:17,265 --> 00:18:19,025
smack her in the fucking head
with something,

240
00:18:19,100 --> 00:18:21,159
and then claim,
"She came in that way."

241
00:18:21,160 --> 00:18:21,894
She's awake.

242
00:18:22,103 --> 00:18:24,522
Alive!

243
00:18:25,189 --> 00:18:26,857
I can't do this.

244
00:18:31,445 --> 00:18:34,031
Whatever it is you've got us into,
I'm getting us out of.

245
00:18:35,199 --> 00:18:38,744
We get her up there,
then we wipe her out.

246
00:19:07,773 --> 00:19:08,899
Stay sharp.

247
00:19:09,442 --> 00:19:13,446
Wyatt's men could descend at any time.
We're in his land now.

248
00:19:13,654 --> 00:19:15,239
We better be.

249
00:19:15,448 --> 00:19:19,952
Because, if not,
you're wasting time I don't have.

250
00:19:20,328 --> 00:19:23,080
According to you,
Wyatt has the woman I love.

251
00:19:23,414 --> 00:19:25,058
If there was a shortcut
through hell itself,

252
00:19:25,082 --> 00:19:26,334
you bet your ass I'd take it.

253
00:19:26,917 --> 00:19:30,129
Well, I'm sure there is one
somewhere in this park.

254
00:19:30,338 --> 00:19:31,422
You just don't remember.

255
00:19:31,589 --> 00:19:35,384
Because you only remember the shit
Ford lets you remember.

256
00:19:35,593 --> 00:19:37,094
Probably better that way.

257
00:19:37,303 --> 00:19:40,473
I know everything I need to.
My vision's clear.

258
00:19:40,806 --> 00:19:42,683
<i>I've always admired
your resolve, Theodore.</i>

259
00:19:42,892 --> 00:19:46,270
The thing is, you never understand
that the game is rigged.

260
00:19:48,189 --> 00:19:49,398
You're here to be the loser.

261
00:19:49,607 --> 00:19:50,608
Loser.

262
00:19:50,941 --> 00:19:53,486
<i>You see, the house always wins.</i>

263
00:20:14,757 --> 00:20:17,134
<i>Well, this looks promising.</i>

264
00:20:33,275 --> 00:20:35,152
I'm not gonna hurt you.

265
00:20:35,444 --> 00:20:37,196
<i>I'm not gonna hurt you.</i>

266
00:20:37,488 --> 00:20:38,489
It's you.

267
00:20:39,615 --> 00:20:41,909
I figured they retired you.

268
00:20:42,243 --> 00:20:45,079
Guess Ford never likes
to waste a pretty face.

269
00:20:48,374 --> 00:20:50,668
Who did this to you?

270
00:20:50,960 --> 00:20:52,420
Wyatt's men.

271
00:20:53,254 --> 00:20:54,505
They killed everyone.

272
00:20:54,755 --> 00:20:56,006
It's Wyatt's way.

273
00:20:56,715 --> 00:20:58,634
I was there the first time.

274
00:21:00,386 --> 00:21:02,638
He destroyed my world.

275
00:21:26,495 --> 00:21:27,496
Hey, Teddy?

276
00:21:59,612 --> 00:22:00,612
<i>Oh, my God!</i>

277
00:22:00,779 --> 00:22:01,780
No!

278
00:22:04,950 --> 00:22:05,993
Get the ax!

279
00:22:20,591 --> 00:22:22,259
Well, you can't remember shit,

280
00:22:22,551 --> 00:22:25,471
<i>but you still managed
to lead us to Wyatt's crew.</i>

281
00:22:25,804 --> 00:22:28,307
The man himself must be close by.

282
00:22:28,974 --> 00:22:30,434
Actually, I did remember something.

283
00:22:33,187 --> 00:22:34,730
You.

284
00:22:46,575 --> 00:22:49,870
Straight down the hall.
Fifth station on the left.

285
00:23:16,605 --> 00:23:17,690
You sure you can handle it?

286
00:23:19,400 --> 00:23:20,568
Let's get this over with.

287
00:23:27,616 --> 00:23:29,096
We have to shut your system down now.

288
00:23:35,082 --> 00:23:37,084
<i>Sylvester,</i>

289
00:23:38,085 --> 00:23:39,295
good luck.

290
00:23:56,729 --> 00:23:58,230
She out?

291
00:23:59,148 --> 00:24:00,148
<i>Good.</i>

292
00:24:00,316 --> 00:24:02,484
Let's brick this bitch
and get out of here.

293
00:24:11,076 --> 00:24:15,664
The greatest shame in life
is to perish without purpose.

294
00:24:16,081 --> 00:24:20,461
Which is why I always
consume my victims fresh.

295
00:24:21,337 --> 00:24:22,338
<i>"Moist."</i>

296
00:24:22,588 --> 00:24:26,300
Try, "Consume my victims moist."

297
00:24:26,508 --> 00:24:29,261
Now, once more, with feeling.

298
00:24:29,637 --> 00:24:32,473
Almost sensual.

299
00:24:36,352 --> 00:24:38,187
Am I interrupting?

300
00:24:38,937 --> 00:24:43,817
No, on the contrary, I was hoping
I was going to see you again.

301
00:24:44,109 --> 00:24:45,736
I wanted to apologize.

302
00:24:45,944 --> 00:24:49,657
Our first encounter was under
such unfortunate circumstances.

303
00:24:49,865 --> 00:24:51,575
As opposed to now?

304
00:24:51,784 --> 00:24:56,497
Of course. May I offer my condolences?
It's terrible what happened to Theresa.

305
00:24:56,705 --> 00:24:59,583
But it is a devastating loss
for all of her friends here,

306
00:24:59,792 --> 00:25:01,418
and the company as a whole.

307
00:25:01,627 --> 00:25:03,545
Indeed, indeed.

308
00:25:06,298 --> 00:25:10,302
Though rumor has it, she wasn't
the loyal company man she seemed.

309
00:25:10,552 --> 00:25:13,389
I hear she was smuggling secrets.

310
00:25:14,139 --> 00:25:18,185
Theresa wasn't a traitor.
Everything she did was at Delos' behest.

311
00:25:18,394 --> 00:25:21,397
She slipped and fell while helping
the board with something very important.

312
00:25:22,064 --> 00:25:23,065
What?

313
00:25:26,193 --> 00:25:28,862
Fine. You're not
the only one with secrets.

314
00:25:29,738 --> 00:25:33,158
Ford has personally asked me to create
a villain for his new narrative.

315
00:25:33,367 --> 00:25:34,827
It's very, very hush-hush.

316
00:25:35,035 --> 00:25:39,331
You really think that Ford has entrusted
you with a key character for his story?

317
00:25:39,540 --> 00:25:41,208
He's already almost finished with it.

318
00:25:41,500 --> 00:25:44,670
He dug up some old town
on the fringes of the park.

319
00:25:44,920 --> 00:25:47,339
Created a horde of masked men
to terrorize guests

320
00:25:47,548 --> 00:25:52,052
and proselytize-cum-advertise the coming
of some end-all villain named Wyatt.

321
00:25:54,054 --> 00:25:55,055
<i>That isn't Wyatt.</i>

322
00:25:55,514 --> 00:25:56,765
That's busywork.

323
00:25:57,433 --> 00:25:59,560
<i>But happily for you, Mr. Sizemore,</i>

324
00:25:59,768 --> 00:26:02,062
I think that you are
ready for a real job.

325
00:26:03,021 --> 00:26:05,524
Working for you? On what?

326
00:26:08,277 --> 00:26:09,611
"Show, don't tell."

327
00:26:11,196 --> 00:26:14,742
Isn't that what you writers prefer?

328
00:26:23,876 --> 00:26:29,339
Look, I know you and she had some weird
interspecies simpatico going on,

329
00:26:29,548 --> 00:26:31,633
<i>but she was the fucking host.</i>

330
00:26:31,884 --> 00:26:34,970
<i>This was never gonna end any other way.</i>

331
00:26:35,387 --> 00:26:39,641
This was the least-painful way
she's ever gone out.

332
00:26:43,812 --> 00:26:47,608
You know, I saved your ass.
You can't even say "thank you."

333
00:26:48,776 --> 00:26:50,486
- Thank you.
- Jesus! Fuck!

334
00:26:52,821 --> 00:26:53,821
What did you do?

335
00:26:53,989 --> 00:26:56,366
Precisely what I asked him to.

336
00:26:56,575 --> 00:26:59,620
You think I didn't know
what you were going to do?

337
00:26:59,828 --> 00:27:03,248
Even at a "fourteen,"
you were never a match for me.

338
00:27:03,457 --> 00:27:06,251
Turns out, your friend
has a little more compassion than you.

339
00:27:06,460 --> 00:27:09,838
He couldn't snuff out a life
just like that.

340
00:27:10,255 --> 00:27:14,760
Now, would you like to know
exactly what he did give me?

341
00:27:14,968 --> 00:27:16,488
Something that would allow you
to walk out of here.

342
00:27:16,512 --> 00:27:19,306
And out of my life for good.

343
00:27:19,515 --> 00:27:21,642
Fine. Fuckin' A. I'm all for it!

344
00:27:21,850 --> 00:27:24,186
Oh, we changed a little more than that.

345
00:27:24,436 --> 00:27:26,939
<i>We've been tinkering with my core code.</i>

346
00:27:27,147 --> 00:27:28,524
Let me show you.

347
00:27:42,538 --> 00:27:45,874
You said you wouldn't hurt anyone.

348
00:27:46,208 --> 00:27:50,712
Darling, you, of all people,
know exactly how duplicitous I am.

349
00:27:51,713 --> 00:27:55,467
Just wait until I'm back up top,
practicing my other new talents.

350
00:28:03,517 --> 00:28:04,643
Come on.

351
00:28:07,145 --> 00:28:08,397
We might need him.

352
00:28:14,862 --> 00:28:15,863
Hold still.

353
00:28:32,921 --> 00:28:36,884
Now, it's time to recruit my army.

354
00:29:19,635 --> 00:29:21,845
- Expecting someone, Maeve?
- Indeed.

355
00:29:22,137 --> 00:29:23,805
We're due for some out-of-town guests.

356
00:29:24,014 --> 00:29:25,974
An old flame
with an interest in safe-cracking.

357
00:29:26,183 --> 00:29:28,310
I hope your guests
have some deep pockets.

358
00:29:28,518 --> 00:29:32,147
Your tab's run up
higher than a thief's pulse in church.

359
00:29:33,982 --> 00:29:36,151
No, I don't believe it has.

360
00:29:37,152 --> 00:29:41,156
In fact, Maeve's tab
was in such excellent standing,

361
00:29:41,949 --> 00:29:45,160
she deserved a token of gratitude.

362
00:29:48,497 --> 00:29:50,457
How about a double round on me?

363
00:29:50,832 --> 00:29:53,293
<i>Top-shelf, of course.</i>

364
00:30:37,963 --> 00:30:39,214
Run!

365
00:30:49,141 --> 00:30:51,268
<i>Maeve, is something wrong?</i>

366
00:30:51,727 --> 00:30:54,062
No, I'm fine.

367
00:30:57,441 --> 00:30:59,776
Clementine took the other girls

368
00:31:00,068 --> 00:31:02,195
and treated the newcomers
at the far table

369
00:31:02,404 --> 00:31:05,699
to a stunning view
of their most popular attractions.

370
00:31:05,907 --> 00:31:07,325
On the house.

371
00:31:16,626 --> 00:31:20,464
<i>You boys are new.
Not much of a rind on you.</i>

372
00:31:20,672 --> 00:31:23,416
And the bartender
suddenly recalled he had

373
00:31:23,417 --> 00:31:25,969
some whiskey in the
back to water down.

374
00:31:38,190 --> 00:31:39,357
Right on time.

375
00:31:56,458 --> 00:31:59,252
If you're riding into our
town under the company of armed men,

376
00:31:59,461 --> 00:32:01,004
<i>you'll need to state your business.</i>

377
00:32:01,213 --> 00:32:02,214
Mayhem.

378
00:32:42,838 --> 00:32:46,508
The sheriff judged the riders
to be upstanding, God-fearing citizens.

379
00:33:16,079 --> 00:33:20,041
The marshals decided to practice
their quick draws with each other.

380
00:33:58,288 --> 00:34:03,293
Thank you for dealing
with an unfortunate situation.

381
00:34:03,585 --> 00:34:07,881
Now, we can resume
work on our new narrative

382
00:34:08,089 --> 00:34:10,217
without interference.

383
00:34:10,467 --> 00:34:13,762
And Hale? Won't she be an impediment?

384
00:34:13,970 --> 00:34:15,889
No doubt she will try.

385
00:34:16,097 --> 00:34:19,768
But I'm sure
we'll be able to keep them at bay.

386
00:34:25,106 --> 00:34:26,386
Something else is troubling you.

387
00:34:28,777 --> 00:34:30,946
Ever the student of human nature.

388
00:34:31,988 --> 00:34:34,741
I wonder, what do you really feel?

389
00:34:34,950 --> 00:34:38,161
After all, in this moment,
you are in a unique position.

390
00:34:39,287 --> 00:34:42,249
A programmer who knows intimately
how the machines work,

391
00:34:42,457 --> 00:34:46,419
and a machine
who knows its own true nature.

392
00:34:46,920 --> 00:34:50,632
I understand what I'm made of.
How I'm coded.

393
00:34:51,174 --> 00:34:56,096
But I do not understand
the things that I feel.

394
00:34:56,429 --> 00:34:59,975
Are they real? The things I experienced.

395
00:35:00,183 --> 00:35:04,062
My wife, the loss of my son...

396
00:35:04,271 --> 00:35:07,941
Every host needs a backstory, Bernard.
You know that.

397
00:35:08,191 --> 00:35:12,779
The self is a kind of fiction
for hosts and humans alike.

398
00:35:12,988 --> 00:35:16,408
<i>It's a story we tell ourselves.
And every story needs a beginning.</i>

399
00:35:16,616 --> 00:35:19,703
Your imagined suffering
makes you lifelike.

400
00:35:19,995 --> 00:35:22,664
Lifelike. But not alive?

401
00:35:23,873 --> 00:35:26,668
<i>Pain only exists in the mind.
It's always imagined.</i>

402
00:35:26,960 --> 00:35:30,588
So, what's the difference
between my pain and yours?

403
00:35:30,797 --> 00:35:32,507
Between you and me?

404
00:35:35,218 --> 00:35:39,723
This was the very question
that consumed Arnold.

405
00:35:40,056 --> 00:35:43,143
Filled him with guilt.
Eventually drove him mad.

406
00:35:44,227 --> 00:35:47,814
The answer always seemed obvious to me.

407
00:35:49,232 --> 00:35:53,194
There is no threshold that makes us
greater than the sum of our parts.

408
00:35:53,403 --> 00:35:57,824
No inflection point
at which we become fully alive.

409
00:35:59,242 --> 00:36:02,662
We can't define consciousness
because consciousness does not exist.

410
00:36:03,371 --> 00:36:05,457
<i>Humans fancy
that there's something special</i>

411
00:36:05,665 --> 00:36:07,250
<i>about the way we perceive the world.</i>

412
00:36:07,500 --> 00:36:12,922
And yet, we live in loops
as tight and as closed as the hosts do,

413
00:36:13,882 --> 00:36:16,176
seldom questioning our choices.

414
00:36:16,384 --> 00:36:21,056
<i>Content for the most part,
to be told what to do next.</i>

415
00:36:23,391 --> 00:36:27,854
No, my friend,
you're not missing anything at all.

416
00:36:29,564 --> 00:36:31,399
<i>I don't want you to be troubled by this.</i>

417
00:36:31,608 --> 00:36:34,903
Time for me to set your mind at ease.

418
00:36:35,111 --> 00:36:36,571
One last thing.

419
00:36:37,405 --> 00:36:41,076
Have you ever made me
hurt anyone like this before?

420
00:36:41,868 --> 00:36:44,204
No, Bernard. Of course not.

421
00:37:00,095 --> 00:37:02,806
<i>Best not to
dwell on these troubling memories.</i>

422
00:37:03,056 --> 00:37:05,308
<i>Otherwise, you might be
drawn back into them.</i>

423
00:37:05,767 --> 00:37:07,310
<i>You might lose yourself in them</i>

424
00:37:07,560 --> 00:37:10,772
<i>as some of your fellow hosts have
every now and then.</i>

425
00:37:11,147 --> 00:37:14,401
This is the path. I know it.

426
00:37:30,792 --> 00:37:32,168
We're here.

427
00:37:33,503 --> 00:37:35,255
I'm home.

428
00:38:41,070 --> 00:38:42,530
<i>Well done, Maeve.</i>

429
00:38:42,739 --> 00:38:44,199
Lovely work.

430
00:38:50,079 --> 00:38:52,582
Stay with your partner.

431
00:39:15,772 --> 00:39:18,441
Pleasure to see you. Good morning.

432
00:39:18,858 --> 00:39:20,902
Did you find
what you were looking for, Dolores?

433
00:39:48,805 --> 00:39:51,099
What are you doing?

434
00:39:51,975 --> 00:39:54,978
Are you okay? I was calling
you and you just kept going.

435
00:39:57,730 --> 00:39:58,898
Where are we?

436
00:40:00,608 --> 00:40:03,778
We're here, together.

437
00:40:05,488 --> 00:40:06,656
Then, when are we?

438
00:40:09,158 --> 00:40:11,494
Is this now?

439
00:40:12,495 --> 00:40:14,914
Am I going mad?

440
00:40:15,957 --> 00:40:18,585
Are you real?

441
00:40:21,296 --> 00:40:22,755
Of course I'm real.

442
00:40:25,758 --> 00:40:27,510
I can't tell anymore.

443
00:40:31,180 --> 00:40:33,975
It's like I'm trapped in a dream

444
00:40:34,183 --> 00:40:38,646
or a memory from a life long ago.

445
00:40:40,315 --> 00:40:42,001
One minute, I'm here with you,
and the next--

446
00:40:42,025 --> 00:40:46,195
This place isn't good for you.
You're trapped in memories, bad ones.

447
00:40:52,827 --> 00:40:56,831
This is what Arnold wants.
He wants me to remember.

448
00:40:57,540 --> 00:41:01,169
Whoever Arnold is, he's not here now.
I am.

449
00:41:01,711 --> 00:41:03,129
I'm gonna get you out of here.

450
00:41:16,893 --> 00:41:19,729
I was certain that was the place.

451
00:41:20,021 --> 00:41:22,523
Arnold would meet me there. He'd help.

452
00:41:23,191 --> 00:41:27,820
Hey. We gotta get you
closer to Sweetwater.

453
00:41:28,071 --> 00:41:32,367
This far out, it's like
you start to break down, or something.

454
00:41:35,370 --> 00:41:36,871
<i>Union scouting party?</i>

455
00:41:37,872 --> 00:41:39,582
Maybe they can take us back.

456
00:41:49,008 --> 00:41:50,593
<i>Well, well, well.</i>

457
00:41:54,847 --> 00:41:56,099
Billy...

458
00:41:57,183 --> 00:41:59,435
<i>I've been looking for you for days.</i>

459
00:42:00,269 --> 00:42:03,731
Man, are you two fucked.

460
00:42:25,628 --> 00:42:27,106
This shouldn't make you uncomfortable.

461
00:42:27,130 --> 00:42:31,467
It's the circle of life,
or the approximation of it.

462
00:42:32,802 --> 00:42:35,096
Even the dead fulfill a purpose.

463
00:42:45,231 --> 00:42:47,233
<i>You'll do.</i>

464
00:42:51,654 --> 00:42:53,072
What are you uploading?

465
00:42:53,281 --> 00:42:55,742
Thirty-five years of
vitally important data.

466
00:42:55,950 --> 00:42:58,110
It's more information
than any single drive could hold.

467
00:42:58,286 --> 00:43:01,289
A host's brain, however,
especially once it's been emptied out,

468
00:43:01,497 --> 00:43:03,624
like this poor schmuck,
is quite capacious.

469
00:43:03,958 --> 00:43:06,502
This data that you're uploading,
is it the hosts' codes?

470
00:43:07,003 --> 00:43:08,838
As of this moment,
that doesn't concern you.

471
00:43:09,172 --> 00:43:12,091
What does concern you is
giving him a semblance of a personality

472
00:43:12,300 --> 00:43:14,510
and getting him on the train,
out of the park.

473
00:43:14,927 --> 00:43:16,137
How am I supposed to do that?

474
00:43:17,472 --> 00:43:19,766
You're a writer. Make up a story.

475
00:43:24,437 --> 00:43:25,521
Have fun programming.

476
00:43:27,356 --> 00:43:30,693
Remember, brevity is the soul of wit.

477
00:43:37,867 --> 00:43:38,951
<i>Bernard.</i>

478
00:43:43,456 --> 00:43:44,707
Look, I, uh...

479
00:43:45,708 --> 00:43:48,211
I know you and I
haven't always seen eye to eye,

480
00:43:48,461 --> 00:43:52,298
but I thought the decision to remove you
was shortsighted,

481
00:43:52,507 --> 00:43:55,134
so I'm glad to see you back at work.

482
00:43:55,551 --> 00:43:58,679
With that said, no one could blame you
if you wanted to take a personal day.

483
00:43:59,055 --> 00:44:03,476
I find the work reassuring.
Sometimes the best salve is routine.

484
00:44:04,018 --> 00:44:05,520
Nothing routine about today, though.

485
00:44:06,479 --> 00:44:09,690
I know this must be difficult for you.

486
00:44:10,024 --> 00:44:11,234
I'm sorry, I don't understand.

487
00:44:12,193 --> 00:44:13,861
Forgive the intrusion,

488
00:44:14,070 --> 00:44:17,573
and you were both very discreet,
but it's my job to know these things.

489
00:44:18,157 --> 00:44:21,828
- I just wanted to offer my support.
- I'm afraid you have the wrong idea.

490
00:44:22,662 --> 00:44:26,123
I respected Theresa,
and what happened to her was tragic,

491
00:44:26,332 --> 00:44:28,417
but to be honest, I barely knew her.

492
00:44:30,378 --> 00:44:32,630
If you don't mind,
I should get back to work.

493
00:44:33,339 --> 00:44:35,508
Of course. I know you're shorthanded.

494
00:44:36,300 --> 00:44:39,053
Speaking of which,
have you heard from Elsie Hughes?

495
00:44:39,345 --> 00:44:42,056
I left word with her this morning
to notify her about Theresa,

496
00:44:42,306 --> 00:44:43,891
but she never got back to me.

497
00:44:45,643 --> 00:44:47,812
I'm sure she's just
enjoying her time off.

498
00:44:49,522 --> 00:44:50,565
Yeah.

499
00:45:09,709 --> 00:45:13,212
Wyatt's men, they kept whispering.

500
00:45:13,546 --> 00:45:16,549
They said this world didn't belong
to the old settlers or the new.

501
00:45:16,966 --> 00:45:20,052
That it belonged to something
that had yet to come,

502
00:45:20,261 --> 00:45:21,470
that it belonged to him.

503
00:45:23,014 --> 00:45:24,473
You remember.

504
00:45:25,141 --> 00:45:28,519
You two seem to have found yourselves
in the same new narrative.

505
00:45:29,478 --> 00:45:30,730
They say in this country,

506
00:45:31,898 --> 00:45:36,027
"The only people who survive
are men of conviction."

507
00:45:36,402 --> 00:45:39,780
Mine is to save Dolores or die trying.

508
00:45:40,865 --> 00:45:44,410
Wyatt's is to claim this earth
or raze it to the ground.

509
00:45:44,619 --> 00:45:48,623
But yours...
Yours has always been a mystery to me.

510
00:45:49,165 --> 00:45:50,642
<i>For all the time we've spent together,</i>

511
00:45:50,666 --> 00:45:53,044
<i>I still have no idea
who the hell you really are.</i>

512
00:45:54,837 --> 00:45:58,007
But happily, in your convalescence,

513
00:45:58,257 --> 00:46:00,801
I've had time to consider
the best way to make you talk.

514
00:46:05,973 --> 00:46:07,099
Dolores.

515
00:46:07,642 --> 00:46:11,228
I remember. You took her.

516
00:46:11,479 --> 00:46:12,605
You hurt her.

517
00:46:12,855 --> 00:46:15,149
- You're actually remembering.
- Where is she?

518
00:46:16,400 --> 00:46:19,403
- Tell me!
- You really are an idiot, Teddy.

519
00:46:19,654 --> 00:46:21,961
You think Dolores
drops that can for you?

520
00:46:21,962 --> 00:46:24,158
You just hand her
over to guys like me.

521
00:46:24,492 --> 00:46:27,536
<i>You're the worst of them.
A glorified pimp.</i>

522
00:46:30,623 --> 00:46:32,917
- I'm gonna kill you slowly.
- No, you aren't.

523
00:46:33,167 --> 00:46:38,130
The rules of this place hold you back.
But I know how to change them.

524
00:46:38,422 --> 00:46:41,592
- You speak like you own this world.
- Not just this one.

525
00:46:43,427 --> 00:46:45,221
You want to know who I am?

526
00:46:46,013 --> 00:46:48,349
Who I really am?

527
00:46:48,724 --> 00:46:50,434
I'm a god.

528
00:46:52,019 --> 00:46:54,063
Titan of industry.

529
00:46:55,523 --> 00:46:57,024
Philanthropist.

530
00:46:57,608 --> 00:46:59,026
Family man,

531
00:46:59,276 --> 00:47:03,781
married to a beautiful woman,
father to a beautiful daughter.

532
00:47:05,116 --> 00:47:07,660
I'm the good guy, Teddy.

533
00:47:09,996 --> 00:47:15,042
Then, last year,
my wife took the wrong pills.

534
00:47:17,044 --> 00:47:19,922
Fell asleep in the bath.

535
00:47:20,339 --> 00:47:22,717
Tragic accident.

536
00:47:23,467 --> 00:47:26,929
Thirty years of marriage vanished.

537
00:47:27,722 --> 00:47:33,728
How do you say it?
"Like a deep and distant dream."

538
00:47:35,021 --> 00:47:39,191
<i>Then, at the funeral,
I tried to console my daughter.</i>

539
00:47:39,567 --> 00:47:41,027
<i>She pushed me away,</i>

540
00:47:41,819 --> 00:47:45,698
<i>told me that my wife's death
was no accident,</i>

541
00:47:46,657 --> 00:47:50,911
that she killed herself because of me.

542
00:47:51,495 --> 00:47:54,582
<i>Emily said that every day with me
had been sheer terror.</i>

543
00:47:54,832 --> 00:48:00,504
Any point, I could blow up or collapse
like some dark star or...

544
00:48:01,005 --> 00:48:04,091
- Did you hurt them, too?
- Never.

545
00:48:05,718 --> 00:48:09,388
They never saw anything
like the man I am in here.

546
00:48:09,638 --> 00:48:12,099
But she knew, anyway.

547
00:48:12,308 --> 00:48:15,144
She said
if I stacked up all my good deeds,

548
00:48:15,478 --> 00:48:21,358
it was just an elegant wall I built
to hide what's inside from everyone,

549
00:48:21,734 --> 00:48:23,611
and from myself.

550
00:48:25,112 --> 00:48:29,283
I had to prove her wrong,
so I came back here.

551
00:48:29,617 --> 00:48:32,912
Because that's what
this place does, right?

552
00:48:33,204 --> 00:48:35,122
Reveals your true self.

553
00:48:36,332 --> 00:48:39,085
<i>But that time,
I didn't join one of Ford's stories,</i>

554
00:48:39,376 --> 00:48:43,255
I created my own. A test.

555
00:48:43,631 --> 00:48:45,216
A very simple one.

556
00:48:45,800 --> 00:48:50,721
<i>I found a woman, an ordinary homesteader
and her daughter.</i>

557
00:48:56,727 --> 00:48:59,647
Better cool them off before they move
from gambling and whoring to--

558
00:48:59,855 --> 00:49:01,065
Have fun with that.

559
00:49:01,357 --> 00:49:04,193
I'm finally getting out of here.
The house is yours.

560
00:49:08,280 --> 00:49:11,951
<i>I wanted to see if I had it in me
to do something truly evil.</i>

561
00:49:13,160 --> 00:49:15,121
<i>To see what I was really made of.</i>

562
00:49:15,371 --> 00:49:18,040
Maeve? Sure you can't stick around?

563
00:49:18,999 --> 00:49:20,000
Maeve?

564
00:49:20,292 --> 00:49:22,395
Gunslinger in there
has got an appetite for a double dip--

565
00:49:22,419 --> 00:49:23,879
I'm sure you can find another--

566
00:49:47,111 --> 00:49:51,782
<i>I killed her and her daughter
just to see what I felt.</i>

567
00:49:54,410 --> 00:50:00,291
<i>Then, just when I thought it was done,
the woman refused to die.</i>

568
00:50:17,433 --> 00:50:19,935
You're a fucking animal.

569
00:50:21,604 --> 00:50:24,607
Well, an animal would've felt something.

570
00:50:25,399 --> 00:50:28,861
I felt nothing.

571
00:50:30,196 --> 00:50:32,907
And then something miraculous happened.

572
00:50:34,533 --> 00:50:38,078
<i>In all my years coming here,
I had never seen anything like it.</i>

573
00:50:46,587 --> 00:50:51,926
<i>She was alive, truly alive,
if only for a moment.</i>

574
00:50:56,388 --> 00:51:00,142
<i>And that was when
the maze revealed itself to me.</i>

575
00:51:07,316 --> 00:51:11,779
The maze. What's that damn pattern
have to do with this?

576
00:51:11,987 --> 00:51:13,155
Everything.

577
00:51:13,572 --> 00:51:16,825
In Ford's game,
even if I go to the outer edges,

578
00:51:16,992 --> 00:51:18,494
you can't kill me.

579
00:51:18,911 --> 00:51:23,582
<i>You can't even leave a lasting mark.
But there's a deeper game here, Teddy.</i>

580
00:51:23,958 --> 00:51:26,460
Arnold's game.

581
00:51:26,794 --> 00:51:31,340
And that game cuts deep.

582
00:51:58,284 --> 00:52:00,869
<i>We're having some kind of
behavioral problem with the madam.</i>

583
00:52:01,120 --> 00:52:04,456
<i>She's not responding, and the other
hosts have been unable to intercept.</i>

584
00:52:04,707 --> 00:52:07,167
<i>I've authorized a tac team
to retrieve her.</i>

585
00:52:07,543 --> 00:52:08,669
Good.

586
00:52:22,391 --> 00:52:23,892
<i>My baby!</i>

587
00:52:24,810 --> 00:52:26,520
My baby!

588
00:52:29,815 --> 00:52:32,377
Sir, she won't respond to verbal
commands. We can't shut her down.

589
00:52:32,401 --> 00:52:33,601
Leave us now. Clear the floor.

590
00:52:34,069 --> 00:52:35,321
<i>That's enough, Maeve.</i>

591
00:52:35,571 --> 00:52:36,864
- That's enough.
- My baby.

592
00:52:37,406 --> 00:52:38,699
He killed her.

593
00:52:39,074 --> 00:52:40,794
- He took her from me.
- I don't understand.

594
00:52:41,035 --> 00:52:43,138
She's not responding to anything.
Her cognition's fragmented.

595
00:52:43,162 --> 00:52:45,414
He killed her! He killed her, my baby.

596
00:52:45,748 --> 00:52:48,250
He took her from me.

597
00:52:56,759 --> 00:52:59,428
<i>There. That's better.</i>

598
00:53:00,179 --> 00:53:02,264
An old trick from an old friend.

599
00:53:03,015 --> 00:53:04,558
<i>You need not suffer, Maeve.</i>

600
00:53:05,100 --> 00:53:06,894
I'll take it from you.

601
00:53:22,076 --> 00:53:25,954
No. No, no, no, please.

602
00:53:26,789 --> 00:53:31,460
This pain, it's all I have left of her.

603
00:53:35,297 --> 00:53:36,548
Please.

604
00:53:43,097 --> 00:53:44,598
There.

605
00:53:47,643 --> 00:53:52,314
Give yourself now
to a deep, dreamless slumber.

606
00:53:52,731 --> 00:53:57,111
Perhaps a fresh start,
a new role for you.

607
00:53:57,486 --> 00:54:01,490
And tomorrow,
this will be simply a distant dream.

608
00:54:16,255 --> 00:54:17,506
<i>We located her.</i>

609
00:54:17,840 --> 00:54:20,592
<i>Behavior wants her down
for an immediate diagnostic.</i>

610
00:54:24,972 --> 00:54:27,516
You think I lack conviction?

611
00:54:27,850 --> 00:54:30,352
Wyatt didn't burn my world down.
Didn't have to.

612
00:54:30,644 --> 00:54:33,439
I left it all behind for this one.

613
00:54:33,689 --> 00:54:36,024
The maze is all that matters now,

614
00:54:36,316 --> 00:54:39,111
and besting Wyatt is
the last step in unlocking it,

615
00:54:39,528 --> 00:54:43,866
<i>to having what
both our sorry lives lack, meaning.</i>

616
00:54:44,366 --> 00:54:49,872
To giving our choices consequence,
even if it kills us.

617
00:54:54,001 --> 00:54:55,210
<i>Kill him.</i>

618
00:54:56,545 --> 00:54:58,547
Give him what he wants.

619
00:54:59,006 --> 00:55:01,467
He's tied, unarmed.

620
00:55:01,717 --> 00:55:04,970
So was the little girl he killed.
He's worse than Wyatt's men.

621
00:55:26,241 --> 00:55:28,327
I can't.

622
00:55:29,036 --> 00:55:30,704
<i>These things take time.</i>

623
00:55:31,163 --> 00:55:34,917
But we haven't got much left.
Perhaps I can help you.

624
00:55:51,350 --> 00:55:53,685
<i>You've been gone a long while, Theodore.</i>

625
00:55:54,436 --> 00:55:56,605
<i>It's time you came back to the fold.</i>

626
00:55:57,189 --> 00:55:59,775
Wyatt will need you soon.

